The worst-case scenario involves a failure or rupture of a one-ton container outside of the Chlorine Storage Room, releasing the entire 2,000 pounds of the container contents within ten minutes. The distance to the endpoint was estimated to be 1.30 miles from the chlorination facility, assuming a wind speed of 3.4 miles/hour and an atmospheric stability rating of Class F. The potential population affected by the worst-case scenario was estimated to be 8,500 persons.

The alternate release scenario involves an accidental pipe leak releasing 1,500 pounds of chlorine gas within ten minutes. The distance to the endpoint was estimated to be 0.20 miles from the chlorination facility, assuming a wind speed of 6.7 miles/hour and an atmospheric rating of Class D. The endpoint determination includes the enclosure of the container within the storage room. The potential population affected by the alternate release scenario was estimated to be 200 persons.

Actuation of the Chlorine Gas Detectors is considered to be an active mitigation measure. Additionally, the chlorine gas piping is vacuum tubing connected directly to the chlorine containers. A loss of vacuum in the tubing immediately stops chlorine gas flow from the containers and virtually eliminates the possibility of a chlorine release due to a piping leak. The Salem Water Treatment Plant is equipped with a Chlorine Gas Scrubber, which is also considered to be an active mitigation measure.

The Salem Water Treatment Plant RMP has the key elements listed below. These elements are aimed at preventing a chlorine release from the chlorination system.

-	High level of operator training and maintenance training;
-	An established preventative maintenance program;
-	Implementation of an audit and inspection program;
-	Use of effective written operating procedures;
-	Implementation of an employee participation program;
-	Use of emergency air supply and container leak kits;
-	Use of a chlorine gas scrubber;
